              <h2>What do microcurie and becquerel measure?</h2>
              <p>
                Both units describe <strong>radioactive activity</strong> – how
                many nuclear decays occur in a given time.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Becquerel (Bq)</strong> – SI unit, defined as one
                  decay per second.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Curie (Ci)</strong> – legacy unit, defined as \(3.7
                  \times 10^{10}\) decays per second.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Microcurie (µCi)</strong> – one millionth of a curie:
                  \(1 \text{ µCi} = 10^{-6} \text{ Ci}\).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                Note: Activity (Bq or µCi) does not directly indicate dose to a
                person (measured in sievert, Sv). Dose depends on radiation
                type, energy, exposure geometry, and shielding.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>How accurate is this microcurie to becquerel converter?</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator uses the exact factor \(1 \text{ Ci} = 3.7 \times
                10^{10} \text{ Bq}\) and performs calculations in
                double‑precision floating point. You can choose the number of
                decimal places for display; the internal computation is more
                precise than the rounded output.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I enter values in scientific notation?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Both input fields accept scientific notation such as
                <code>1e6</code>, <code>3.7E4</code>, or <code>2.5e-3</code>.
                This is especially useful for very large or very small
                activities.
              </p>

              <h3>When should I use µCi vs Bq?</h3>
              <p>
                Use <strong>Bq</strong> for SI‑compliant scientific work,
                regulatory reporting, and most modern publications. Use
                <strong>µCi</strong> when working with older literature, certain
                nuclear medicine protocols, or equipment that still reports in
                curies or microcuries.
              </p>
